      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0749">
               <p>Mary Freeman, was a second cousin of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0179.xml"
                     />Ebenezer Blackwell</persName>, born in <placeName>England</placeName> but
                  descended on her maternal side from Italian aristocratic roots. She was educated
                  at a convent in <placeName>Rome</placeName>, and remained a devout Roman Catholic
                  her whole life. Through the Blackwells Freeman became close friends with
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>Charles</persName> and
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2191.xml"/>Sarah Wesley</persName> and
                  their children (perhaps influencing their son <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2190.xml"/>Samuel</persName> in his decision to convert
                  to the Church of <placeName>Rome</placeName>). Freeman never married, but about
                     <date when="1784">1784</date> she formally changed her name to Mary Freeman
                  Shepherd, in honor of her uncle <persName>Nathaniel Shepherd</persName>, who was
                  her godfather and benefactor. See William Urwick, <hi rend="italic">Nonconformity
                     in Herts</hi> (<placeName>London</placeName>, <date when="1884">1884</date>),
                  189–90.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
